A 25-year-old aluminum fabricator in Lagos, Ibrahim Ali, on Friday pleaded guilty   to unlawfully stabbing a man on the face. Ali, who resides at No. 1 Olufunmilayo St., Igando, Lagos, admitted before an Ikeja Magistrates’ Court that he stabbed one Mr Ojo Oluwaseun with a broken bottle. Following his guilty plea, the Magistrate, Mrs M. O. Tanimola, ordered that Ali should be kept behind bars pending review of the facts of the case and his sentencing. The accused is facing a four-count charge of conspiracy, membership of unlawful society, assault and breach of peace. Earlier, the Police Insp. Aondohemba Koti told the court that the accused committed the offences, with others still at large, on Oct. 14 at 3.00p. m. at Olarewaju Street, Mushin, Lagos. Koti said that the accused stabbed  Oluwaseun on the left side of his face, following a disagreement. He also submitted that the accused conducted  himself in a manner likely to cause breach of peace by belonging to an unlawful society known as ‘Eiye’ Fraternity. He noted that the offences violated Sections 42, 168, 173 and 411 of the Criminal Law of Lagos State, 2015, (Revised). The News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reports that Section 173 stipulates a three-year jail for assault occasioning harm, while 411 provides for two years’ imprisonment  for conspiracy. The magistrate fixed Dec. 19 for review of the facta of the case and sentencing. (NAN